<br>
There is never only 1 cause for anything.<br>
<br>
The causes contributing to the death of the people in that van include, but are by no means limited to:<br>
<br>
1) The US has chosen to remove Saddam from power.<br>
2) Saddam Hussein refused to comply wiht the UN<br>
3) The opinions/feelings of the civilians in question<br>
4) The recent events with the suicide bomber not long before<br>
5) The laws of physics<br>
etc etc, there are literally an infinite number of causes that are part of this all happening.<br>
<br>
You cannot single out any one and claim it is the only cause.<br>
<br>
If a drunk driver hits an innocent woman walking across the street, what do we say the cause of her death is?  In part it's that the man got drunk, in part it may be because the woman's husband ate all the ice cream and didn't buy more so she went out to get some.  Most people will blame the drunk driver.<br>
<br>
My point is that causation for any event is actually complex, however, if something bad happens, we tend to associate blame with the person we perceive as doing the evil act.<br>
<br>
Thus, if you perceive that the Americans are liberating the oppressed Iraqis from an evil tyrant, and the people in the van are attempting to kill them, your tendancy would be to ascribe blame to the people in the van.  If you think that the evil imperialist Americans are invading the innocent Iraqi utopia then you will tend to ascribe blame to the Iraqis.<br>
<br>
Neither is really right unless one view or the other of the conflict as a whole is correct.  It's just 2 different faces of the same issue, which brings us back to the same old argument again...<br>
<br>
